1
00:00:00,436 --> 00:00:08,509
Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa.

2
00:00:09,512 --> 00:00:17,725
Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa.

3
00:00:18,246 --> 00:00:23,035
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed and noble, self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:25,140 --> 00:00:36,076
So last month we did courage, which doesn't actually come up as a separate item in the 10 perfections, the 10 virtues to be perfected.

5
00:00:37,037 --> 00:00:41,844
But I suppose you could fit it into Adhitana, which means the sort of resolute resolution.

6
00:00:42,185 --> 00:00:44,088
We'll do that another time anyway.

7
00:00:44,109 --> 00:00:51,198
But it does have a what we talked about was courage is doing something, you know, like achieving something.

8
00:00:51,853 --> 00:00:54,097
even though it's very difficult one way or the other.

9
00:00:54,317 --> 00:01:00,067
But there's a passive side to courage, which is, of course, patient forbearance.

10
00:01:00,527 --> 00:01:02,030
Now, the Buddha is very big on that.

11
00:01:04,954 --> 00:01:06,957
He encourages us to develop it.

12
00:01:06,998 --> 00:01:07,799
So this is what he says.

13
00:01:07,900 --> 00:01:12,968
Things like patient endurance is the supreme austerity.

14
00:01:14,078 --> 00:01:22,873
Whoever endures abuse, assault and imprisonment without animosity, and who has forbearance as one's strength,

15
00:01:23,004 --> 00:01:26,871
as one's mighty army, I call a Brahmin.

16
00:01:26,891 --> 00:01:32,019
So a Brahmin in the Buddha's understanding is someone who's achieved something.

17
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:41,456
He was always poking fun at the Brahmins who were pretending to be the spiritual leaders of society.

18
00:01:41,496 --> 00:01:43,159
Many of them were a bit corrupt, I think.

19
00:01:43,459 --> 00:01:45,283
I'm sure there were some good ones there.

20
00:01:46,242 --> 00:01:54,192
He who holds back rising anger like a rolling chariot, him I call a real driver.

21
00:01:54,662 --> 00:02:18,611
other people are but holding the reins and there's a verse here from the terra gata which is the collected verses of the elders this is um the senior monks not the nuns forbearance is the highest virtue forbearance is the highest self-control forbearance is the highest happiness

22
00:02:18,592 --> 00:02:24,479
So there's a lot going on for this virtue of forbearance.

23
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:31,449
And we'll look at one or two areas, all those areas where we feel insulted, slandered and all that sort of stuff.

24
00:02:32,210 --> 00:02:35,935
Then there's the hardships and adversities that come to us through life.

25
00:02:36,955 --> 00:02:40,700
Then we're, of course, cultivating patience with others.

26
00:02:41,237 --> 00:02:48,705
Then there's this inner bearing with reactivity, letting go of our inner reactions to things.

27
00:02:49,407 --> 00:02:52,590
And finally, patience with the spiritual path.

28
00:02:54,211 --> 00:02:57,675
And in so doing, we sort of build up this inner strength and resilience.

29
00:02:58,616 --> 00:03:01,939
You know, when everything falls apart, there's that ability to bounce back.

30
00:03:04,383 --> 00:03:10,248
So the first one, just in dealing with insults, criticism, slander,

31
00:03:12,423 --> 00:03:19,229
So it's important for us to face these things when they come up instead of retaliating, becoming upset.

32
00:03:19,570 --> 00:03:27,058
See, you have to develop this patience and maintain equanimity, which is difficult, of course.

33
00:03:27,079 --> 00:03:32,685
I mean, often the best thing is, is to approach the person who's done this to you, you know, and have a little discussion with them.

34
00:03:34,447 --> 00:03:35,527
That's before you hit them.

35
00:03:38,713 --> 00:03:45,663
Now, there's an occasion here where the Buddha is actually, well, abused by somebody.

36
00:03:45,743 --> 00:03:47,506
So I shall read out this little bit.

37
00:03:48,627 --> 00:03:59,203
At one time, the Buddha was staying near Rajagaha in the bamboo grove, the squirrel's feeding ground, and the Brahmin Bharadwaja, the rood,

38
00:03:59,469 --> 00:04:10,020
heard a rumor that a Brahmin of the Bharadvaja clan had gone forth from the lay life to homelessness in the presence of the ascetic Gautama.

39
00:04:10,521 --> 00:04:12,324
So remember, that's his family name, Gautama.

40
00:04:13,063 --> 00:04:19,810
Angry and displeased, he went to the Buddha and abused and insulted him with rude and harsh words.

41
00:04:20,291 --> 00:04:25,156
And when he'd spoken, the Buddha said to him, what do you think, Brahmin?

42
00:04:25,137 --> 00:04:31,250
Do friends and colleagues, relatives and family members and guests still come to visit you?

43
00:04:32,033 --> 00:04:33,978
Well, sometimes they do, Master Gautama.

44
00:04:34,619 --> 00:04:38,809
And do you then serve them fresh and cooked foods and savouries?

45
00:04:39,228 --> 00:04:40,309
Sometimes I do.

46
00:04:40,970 --> 00:04:44,514
And if they don't accept it, Brahmin, who does it belong to?

47
00:04:44,574 --> 00:04:47,297
Well, in that case, it still belongs to me.

48
00:04:47,317 --> 00:04:55,627
In the same way, Brahmin, when you abuse, harass and attack us, who do not abuse, harass and attack?

49
00:04:56,007 --> 00:04:57,108
We don't accept it.

50
00:04:57,389 --> 00:04:58,470
It belongs to you.

51
00:04:59,170 --> 00:05:01,033
Brahmin, it still belongs to you.

52
00:05:02,043 --> 00:05:12,704
Someone who, when abused, harassed and attacked, abuses, harasses and attacks in return, is said to eat the food and have a reaction to it.

53
00:05:13,346 --> 00:05:17,014
But we neither eat your food nor do we have a reaction to it.

54
00:05:17,334 --> 00:05:19,098
It still belongs to you, Brahmin.

55
00:05:19,158 --> 00:05:21,182
It still belongs to you.

56
00:05:21,161 --> 00:05:27,992
Now, the Brahmin mistakes the Buddha's assertive forthrightness for aggressive bluntness.

57
00:05:28,675 --> 00:05:34,605
And he says, ah, he says, the king and the retinue believe that Master Gautama is a perfected one.

58
00:05:35,225 --> 00:05:36,648
And yet he still gets angry.

59
00:05:37,428 --> 00:05:47,406
So one of the signs of somebody who's perfected, of course, that they don't get angry or at least when they if they do show anger, they're only they're only putting it on.

60
00:05:47,386 --> 00:06:00,863
Anyway, he says, the Buddha replies, for one free of anger, tamed, living in balance, freed with by right understanding, one who is composed and at peace, where would anger come from?

61
00:06:01,404 --> 00:06:05,529
When you get angry at an angry person, you just make things worse for yourself.

62
00:06:06,190 --> 00:06:10,836
And when you don't get angry at an angry person, you win a battle hard to win.

63
00:06:12,238 --> 00:06:14,322
When you know that the other is angry,

64
00:06:14,656 --> 00:06:21,548
You act for the good of both yourself and the other if you're mindful and stay calm.

65
00:06:21,949 --> 00:06:29,103
People unfamiliar with this teaching consider one who heals both oneself and the other to be a fool.

66
00:06:30,973 --> 00:06:39,125
Anyway, this seems to have convinced Bharadvajiv practically bowled over because he then says, oh, excellent Master Gautama.

67
00:06:39,245 --> 00:06:44,733
And before you know it, he's taken refuge in the Buddha to his teaching and to the order.

68
00:06:45,134 --> 00:06:46,416
And he wants to become a monk.

69
00:06:48,399 --> 00:06:53,447
So then he receives the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha's presence.

70
00:06:53,507 --> 00:06:57,673
And not long after the ordination, the Venerable Bharadvajar the Rude,

71
00:06:58,192 --> 00:07:08,610
living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life.

72
00:07:09,430 --> 00:07:18,706
He lived having achieved it with his own insight, the goal for which people rightly go forth from lay life into homelessness.

73
00:07:18,886 --> 00:07:20,168
And he understood

74
00:07:20,485 --> 00:07:21,687
Rebirth is ended.

75
00:07:21,728 --> 00:07:24,557
The spiritual journey has been completed.

76
00:07:24,617 --> 00:07:27,124
What had to be done has been done.

77
00:07:27,464 --> 00:07:30,593
There is no return to any state of becoming.

78
00:07:31,255 --> 00:07:34,966
And the Venerable Bharadwaja became one of the perfected ones.

79
00:07:36,466 --> 00:07:43,536
So I don't know how you handle when you feel angry about what somebody's done or said about you.

80
00:07:45,358 --> 00:07:56,634
But I if somebody sort of has been angry with me, I've learned to sort of just listen to what they say rather than, you know, even though there's a

81
00:07:56,615 --> 00:08:01,603
there's a reaction here, I put my whole attention on actually what they're saying.

82
00:08:02,365 --> 00:08:12,762
And in so doing, I then reply to what they're saying and maintain at least an outward sign of non-anger, non-reactivity.

83
00:08:13,362 --> 00:08:17,589
And that normally allows them to cool down a bit.

84
00:08:17,810 --> 00:08:21,896
And then hopefully there's some discussion before anything gets worse.

85
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:27,954
And that leads us, of course, to having patience with others, you know.

86
00:08:27,973 --> 00:08:33,051
Also, you know, we meet people who just get up our noses.

87
00:08:33,402 --> 00:08:38,730
And somehow we have to cultivate this acceptance, this patience with them, you know.

88
00:08:38,750 --> 00:08:43,099
So, of course, responding with a certain understanding and compassion.

89
00:08:43,759 --> 00:08:48,467
Now, there was a case at Candaboda, which was where I stayed for quite some time.

90
00:08:49,249 --> 00:08:50,331
A schizophrenic came.

91
00:08:50,451 --> 00:08:53,736
At least he told us he'd been diagnosed as a schizophrenic.

92
00:08:53,756 --> 00:08:56,861
And he'd obviously stopped taking the pills.

93
00:08:57,668 --> 00:09:12,552
And he was doing some very funny things, like, for instance, meditating in the nude, which in the East is a bit off, and sometimes showering, public showering, you know, where you go to the open well and pour water over yourself.

94
00:09:13,413 --> 00:09:17,600
And he was doing some other silly things that were disturbing people.

95
00:09:17,918 --> 00:09:28,283
So the people there, I didn't know this was going on because the place was sort of a little bit far away from my own hut, you know.

96
00:09:28,937 --> 00:09:32,102
And so they went to the abbot and complained about him, you see.

97
00:09:32,202 --> 00:09:33,264
But the abbot did nothing.

98
00:09:33,465 --> 00:09:36,710
Eventually, in sort of a bit of desperation, they came to see me.

99
00:09:36,750 --> 00:09:43,179
And I said, well, I said, I'll go up and see the Venerable Upalian and see what he'll do, you know.

100
00:09:43,701 --> 00:09:47,346
So I went up and expressed their annoyance.

101
00:09:47,626 --> 00:09:51,773
Well, the fact that they felt their practice was being heavily disturbed.

102
00:09:52,394 --> 00:09:54,917
And he didn't do anything.

103
00:09:55,157 --> 00:10:04,167
Now, I never knew whether it's because he didn't want to confront this man or whether it was a teaching of just bearing up with what is unpleasant.

104
00:10:04,606 --> 00:10:06,889
And it's usually the unpleasant which disappears.

105
00:10:07,811 --> 00:10:08,792
Usually it's the opposite.

106
00:10:08,892 --> 00:10:12,176
Somebody disturbs you and we tend to move away.

107
00:10:12,796 --> 00:10:17,341
But actually, if you just hang on in there, they usually give up and disappear.

108
00:10:18,022 --> 00:10:19,683
So this was a big teaching for me.

109
00:10:22,802 --> 00:10:29,556
uh the second one of course the other one is endurance in adversity you know when things fall apart

110
00:10:30,110 --> 00:10:41,530
When you when you have an illness or something like that, or you lose a close friend or a family member or somebody at work leaves whom you had a good relationship with.

111
00:10:42,211 --> 00:10:49,264
All those things, just the ordinary adversities of life that just come our way, you know, just being able to accept them.

112
00:10:49,806 --> 00:10:51,067
You know, this is the way it is.

113
00:10:51,128 --> 00:10:52,289
That's the big phrase, isn't it?

114
00:10:52,370 --> 00:10:53,873
Just to accept it.

115
00:10:53,852 --> 00:11:02,562
And sometimes I found it helpful to write out the situation so that I'm clear as to what's actually happening.

116
00:11:03,261 --> 00:11:10,288
And that allows this, whatever has arisen, anger, disappointment, grief, despair, all that sort of stuff.

117
00:11:10,308 --> 00:11:12,611
It just eventually sort of burns itself out.

118
00:11:13,893 --> 00:11:23,842
I mean, as you know, recently I had some really bad trouble with a slipped disc, you know, which gave me,

119
00:11:23,822 --> 00:11:27,727
which stopped me from walking actually, the sciatica.

120
00:11:28,447 --> 00:11:45,447
And funnily enough, you know, having accepted the situation this year, this is the first time I've actually walked around the meadows twice a day and really sort of enjoyed the way that nature's come alive over the spring.

121
00:11:46,109 --> 00:11:48,631
So it's not been that heavy.

122
00:11:50,754 --> 00:11:55,341
And it all comes down to this basic acceptance, you know, this is the way it is.

123
00:11:55,461 --> 00:11:56,243
This is this.

124
00:11:56,583 --> 00:12:02,472
If you keep saying that to yourself, you know, just sort of banging it into your head, you know, this is the way it is.

125
00:12:03,014 --> 00:12:05,277
And then just letting the heart relax around that.

126
00:12:05,517 --> 00:12:06,197
This is the way it is.

127
00:12:06,719 --> 00:12:09,202
And then the possibilities usually turn up.

128
00:12:10,785 --> 00:12:16,451
I mean, we went through that very strange period of lockdown, you know, that was really weird.

129
00:12:17,292 --> 00:12:22,517
And for many people, it was just an opportunity to do stuff they always wanted to do.

130
00:12:22,597 --> 00:12:24,278
Now they can't do what they usually do.

131
00:12:25,220 --> 00:12:30,325
So take up new hobbies and writing and music and stuff like that.

132
00:12:30,985 --> 00:12:34,568
So it is very much a case of bearing with it.

133
00:12:34,708 --> 00:12:36,892
And it begins with this acceptance, you know.

134
00:12:37,511 --> 00:12:40,455
And then, of course, we find that it's not so bad.

135
00:12:40,755 --> 00:12:47,865
However, there can be situations which are very painful.

136
00:12:47,884 --> 00:12:52,551
And there's a discourse here called the Parable of the Saw.

137
00:12:52,731 --> 00:12:55,115
I'm sure many of you have heard it.

138
00:12:55,836 --> 00:13:08,231
And this is the Buddha says, you know, even with terrible physical pain, monks, even if bandits were to sever you savagely, limb by limb with a two-handed saw,

139
00:13:08,870 --> 00:13:14,916
He who gave rise to a mind of hate towards them would not be carrying out my teachings.

140
00:13:16,677 --> 00:13:20,601
Monks, even in such a situation, you should train yourselves thus.

141
00:13:21,383 --> 00:13:36,639
Neither shall our minds be affected by this, nor for this matter shall we give vent to evil words, but we shall remain in full concern and pity with a mind of love, and we shall not give in to hatred.

142
00:13:37,178 --> 00:13:38,100
On the contrary,

143
00:13:38,788 --> 00:13:49,962
We shall live projecting thoughts of universal love to those very persons, making them, as well as the whole world, the object of our thoughts.

144
00:13:50,044 --> 00:13:55,432
of universal love, thoughts that have grown great, exalted, and measureless.

145
00:13:56,053 --> 00:14:03,203
We shall dwell radiating these thoughts, which are a void of hostility and ill-will.

146
00:14:03,544 --> 00:14:05,988
In this way, you should train yourselves."

147
00:14:06,830 --> 00:14:09,232
That's a bit of a demand, isn't it?

148
00:14:09,253 --> 00:14:15,241
In fact, when I once said this in a talk, somebody said, well, the Buddha had a great sense of humor.

149
00:14:18,596 --> 00:14:24,764
So, you know, bearing up with things just gives us that sense of resilience, you know.

150
00:14:26,605 --> 00:14:35,255
Now, when it comes to our inner practice, I mean, this is also to do with how we react to what's happening to us on the outside.

151
00:14:35,316 --> 00:14:41,481
But of course, it also has an effect of how we react to ourselves within ourselves.

152
00:14:41,802 --> 00:14:47,389
And all this comes under that quality of desire, reaction, reactivity.

153
00:14:47,538 --> 00:15:01,639
And here again, there's an importance to be able to bear with ourselves, to bear with our own thoughts and emotions, sensations and stuff like that, just so that we can develop a clarity of mind.

154
00:15:02,541 --> 00:15:06,086
I was here reminded of Brian Keenan.

155
00:15:06,447 --> 00:15:08,370
Some of you remember this.

156
00:15:08,389 --> 00:15:13,157
So he was captured by Shiite militiamen.

157
00:15:13,136 --> 00:15:16,763
Oh, I thought I had the date, but it goes back a bit.

158
00:15:17,144 --> 00:15:20,769
1990, that's when he wrote the book.

159
00:15:20,789 --> 00:15:27,201
And luckily, he had another person, John McCarthy, who shared the cell with him.

160
00:15:27,240 --> 00:15:31,368
And for four years, they lived in this really horrible imprisonment state.

161
00:15:31,388 --> 00:15:34,452
If you read the book, Evil Cradling, it really is a shocker.

162
00:15:35,817 --> 00:15:40,961
And he came out of it, from all intents and purposes, really strengthened.

163
00:15:41,701 --> 00:15:54,813
And I remember when I read the book, there's a point there where he has an insight into thought, which I thought was a spiritual insight, actually.

164
00:15:56,635 --> 00:16:03,001
But unfortunately, there was another man there who was an American who really was broken by it.

165
00:16:03,121 --> 00:16:05,283
It's a sad story.

166
00:16:05,264 --> 00:16:11,447
So some people just I mean, now we've got this business in, you know, Ukraine and Russia.

167
00:16:12,090 --> 00:16:15,442
So there are people having to go through this sort of stuff.

168
00:16:16,638 --> 00:16:22,009
So the final thing is, of course, patience with our spiritual progress.

169
00:16:22,331 --> 00:16:28,404
So you have to be careful here because lots of people say to me, you know, well, I don't feel I'm progressing.

170
00:16:30,129 --> 00:16:35,541
And that means normally that we've got some idea as to where we ought to be.

171
00:16:35,520 --> 00:16:44,250
what we ought to have achieved by now, some idea of what the insight practices are, some idea about nibbani.

172
00:16:44,850 --> 00:16:46,692
So this can be very debilitating.

173
00:16:46,753 --> 00:16:59,827
And I always think it's best just to put that to the side, you know, because the spiritual practice, so long as you're making that effort, that sort of gentle effort to just keep mindful, keep working with it, it's bound to move.

174
00:16:59,888 --> 00:17:02,811
The Buddha talks of it like the growth of a tree.

175
00:17:02,791 --> 00:17:07,641
you know, from a very seed and how long it takes for that tree to finally fruit.

176
00:17:08,482 --> 00:17:16,319
So it is a case of really having patience with that, but also not getting into it at all, really.

177
00:17:16,420 --> 00:17:18,183
It just happens naturally.

178
00:17:18,265 --> 00:17:34,009
And I think that it's much more wise in a way just to work with our negative mental states, because as they begin to lose their power over us, there's a greater clarity anyway.

179
00:17:34,769 --> 00:17:36,071
It's just part of the practice.

180
00:17:39,982 --> 00:17:44,888
In fact, somebody complains to him about how hard the practice is, you see.

181
00:17:45,190 --> 00:17:49,055
And the Buddha says, well, he said, in the end, you achieve nibbana.

182
00:17:49,736 --> 00:17:53,180
And the questioner says, yeah, nibbana, so what?

183
00:17:54,060 --> 00:17:58,827
He says, well, he says, when you get there, you are happy and with it contented.

184
00:17:59,669 --> 00:18:01,451
Tutti sukha vahati.

185
00:18:02,071 --> 00:18:02,952
Tutti frutti.

186
00:18:04,942 --> 00:18:17,198
So we have to be careful about that, not wanting to have some idea as to what spiritual insights or what nibbana is, and just have that sort of confidence that we're moving that way.

187
00:18:20,301 --> 00:18:31,876
So we've been looking at this patient forbearance, which the Buddha sort of really highlights as an important practice, how to work with people who

188
00:18:32,363 --> 00:18:37,219
slander us or abuse us or say nasty things to us.

189
00:18:38,522 --> 00:18:42,998
We have to work with hardships and adversity when it comes our way, you know.

190
00:18:43,518 --> 00:19:02,566
Cultivating patience towards others and then reactivity either towards others, but spiritually in the practice, this reactivity that we have within ourselves, you know, driven by desire, wanting something, not wanting something, always trying to make the world comfortable.

191
00:19:03,807 --> 00:19:08,095
And then finally, just having patience with the spiritual path.

192
00:19:08,115 --> 00:19:10,317
The Buddha says it's a gradual path.

193
00:19:12,744 --> 00:19:13,307
Very good.

194
00:19:14,390 --> 00:19:27,867
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your development of patient forbearance, you will achieve the final liberation from all suffering sooner rather than later.

